definition: "Luteinizing hormone (LH) is a gonadotropin — a glycoprotein hormone produced and secreted by gonadotroph cells in the anterior pituitary gland — that plays a central role in reproductive function in both sexes. In women, LH drives the mid-cycle surge that triggers ovulation: as the dominant follicle matures and estrogen rises to a threshold level, a sudden positive feedback effect on the hypothalamus and pituitary produces the LH surge — a dramatic 5–10× rise in LH over 24–36 hours that causes the follicle to rupture and release the egg. After ovulation, LH stimulates the corpus luteum (the remnant of the ruptured follicle) to produce progesterone during the luteal phase. In men, LH acts on Leydig cells in the testes, directly stimulating testosterone synthesis. LH secretion in men is pulsatile — driven by GnRH pulses from the hypothalamus — and testosterone feeds back negatively to suppress both GnRH and LH, forming the core regulatory loop of the male HPG axis."
why_it_matters: "LH is the missing piece in most hormonal workups — the signal that distinguishes whether a hormone problem originates in the pituitary (too little signaling) or the gonads (failing to respond). In men with low testosterone, the LH value immediately narrows the differential: high LH with low testosterone means the testes are being driven maximally but failing to produce adequate testosterone (primary hypogonadism — testicular failure). Low LH with low testosterone means the pituitary is not sending adequate signal (secondary hypogonadism — pituitary or hypothalamic problem, possibly a prolactinoma). This distinction completely changes the workup, treatment options, and prognosis. In women, the LH:FSH ratio is a valuable diagnostic tool for PCOS — elevated LH relative to FSH (LH:FSH ratio > 2:1 or 3:1) is a characteristic but not universal pattern. And in perimenopause, LH rises alongside FSH as the ovaries become less responsive, providing confirmatory evidence of the hormonal transition."

standard_range: "Women — follicular phase: 2–15 mIU/mL · Women — mid-cycle surge: 22–105 mIU/mL · Women — luteal phase: 0.6–19 mIU/mL · Women — postmenopausal: 16–64 mIU/mL · Men: 1.7–8.6 mIU/mL"
